text: Alnumycins A2 and A3: new inverse-epimeric pairs stereoisomeric to alnumycin A1 Terhi Oja a, Petri Tähtinen b, Nadine Dreiack a,b, Pekka Mäntsälä a, Jarmo Niemi a, Mikko Metsä-Ketelä a, Karel D. Klika a,⇑ a Department of Biochemistry and Food Chemistry, University of Turku, Vatselankatu 2, FIN-20014, Turku, Finland b Department of Chemistry, University of Turku, Vatselankatu 2, FIN-20014, Turku, Finland Article history: Received 28 March 2012 Accepted 1 May 2012 Available online 13 June 2012 Bacterial aromatic polyketides are complex natural products richly endowed with biological properties and with a number of established medicinal applications,1 including their use as antibiot- ics. Their structures typically consist of a polyaromatic aglycone chromophore with various attendant deoxysugars as sidechains. In many cases, such as the anthracycline antibiotics doxorubicin2 and aclacinorubin3 and the aureolic acid mithramycin,4 the presence of a carbohydrate moiety is imperative for exhibiting biological activity. Naturally occurring alnumycin5–8 {originally described as a single compound,5–7 then a pair of stereoisomers,8 now herein reported as a set of six stereoisomeric compounds alnumycins A1–3 1–3, Fig. 1} is especially an interesting member of the class since instead of the common deoxysugars, it possesses a highly unusual 40-hydroxy-50-hydroxymethyl-20,70-dioxane moi- ety which is furthermore attached atypically via a C(cid:2)C bond to the isochromanequinone aglycone, prealnumycin 4. 0957-4166/$ - see front matter (cid:2) 2012 Elsevier Ltd. Similar to alnumycin A1 {(2)-(1R,10RS,40RS,50SR)}, each of these natu- rally occurring compounds is also a pair of C-1 inverse epimers. The relative conﬁgurations of the dioxane ring sidechains were assigned on the basis of 1H NMR NOE contacts and molecular modeling using den- sity functional theory (DFT) at the M06-2X/6-31G(d) level of theory. The absolute conﬁgurations of C-1 and the determination of inverse epimeric relationships were achieved by experimental electronic circu- lar dichroism (ECD) measurements, with both aspects conﬁrmed by using the chiral derivatizing agent (CDA) Mosher0s acid chloride {a-methoxy-a-triﬂuorophenylacetyl chloride (MTPACl)} to effect enantio- differentiation. The absolute conﬁgurations of the dioxane ring using the CDA could only be effected in the case of alnumycin A1, the results of which were in agreement with previous assignments. The diox- ane ring conformational mobility and the likely interaction between the MTPA groups coupled with the structural novelty of the diols in the dioxane ring with respect to CDA analysis precluded an absolute con- ﬁguration assignment for alnumycins A2 and A3 based on empirical comparisons or by computational analysis of through-space NMR shieldings (TSNMRS) emanating from the phenyl groups of the MTPA moieties. The gross structure of the stereoisomers described herein as alnumycins A1–3 1–3, isolated from a culture broth of Streptomy- ces sp. CM020,11 has previously been reported under various mon- ikers, such as BE-41956A,5 alnumycin,6 and K1115 B1.7 Tatsuta et al.8 identiﬁed two stereoisomers, denoted as K1115 B1a and K1115 B1b with absolute conﬁgurations of (1R,10R,40R,50S) and (1R,10S,40S,50R), respectively, based on stereospeciﬁc synthesis. Thus, 1a and 1b {compounds K1115 B1a and K1115 B1b herein are denoted as alnumycin A1a 1a and alnumycin A1b 1b, respec- tively} are not epimers of one another and their special relation- ship, in that they differ from each other in their conﬁgurations at all stereogenic centers bar one, has realized the concept of inverse epimers.(cid:2)12 Since C-1 is located far from the other stereocenters lo- cated in the dioxane ring, it only has a minimal inﬂuence resulting in exceedingly similar NMR spectra for the two stereoisomers present in the inverse epimeric pair 1. However, a question arises upon encountering compound pairs such as 1–3: do the stereoisomers constitute a pair of epimers or a pair of inverse epimers? Analytical challenges occur because the differential properties, for example, (cid:2) Deﬁnition: Inverse epimers are stereoisomers containing more than two stere- ogenic centers that differ in their conﬁguration at all stereogenic centers bar one. In other words, the inverse of the epimeric case. (cid:2) 2012 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.

The recently described9 notation for indicating relative stereochemistry as an extension to the Natta projection convention10 is used and for which the ‘2’ near to the C-10 atom or within the name, for example, 1a + 1b (cid:3) (2)-(1R,10RS,40RS,50SR)-alnumycin A1 1, indicates that the number of stereoisomers present in the sample or under consideration is two. spectroscopic properties, of each compound in comparison to the other under achiral conditions between a compound and its epimer are precisely the same as that between the said compound and its inverse epimer. This is because the epimer and the inverse epimer are in fact enantiomers of one another and whether the differences between a compound and its (inverse) epimer are large or small is irrelevant to the conclusion of the actual stereochemical relationship between the two compounds. Thus, in addition to the alnumycin A1 pair of C-1 inverse epimers 1 {(2)-(1R,10RS,40RS,50SR)} reported previously, four new stereoisomers, alnumycins A2 2 {(2)-(1R,10RS,40SR,50SR)} and A3 3 {(2)-(1R,10RS,40SR,50RS)}, have been isolated in this work and are reported herein. The structures of 2 and 3 are also depicted in Fig- ure 1 and, as implied, each is also a pair of C-1 inverse epimers. Proof of the absolute conﬁgurations of C-1 and determination of the inverse epimeric relationships were effected by electronic cir- cular dichroism (ECD) measurements. Both aspects were then con- ﬁrmed, together with a rendering of the holemicity of the C-1 stereogenic center, by use of the chiral derivatizing agent (CDA) Mosher’s acid chloride13,14 {a-methoxy-a-triﬂuorophenylacetyl chloride (MTPACl)} to effect enantiodifferentiation.(cid:3)15

The application of CDAs for absolute conﬁguration determina- tion, especially for MTPA-derivatized substrates, has been thor- (cid:3) Deﬁnition: Enantiodifferentiation is the identiﬁcation of an enantiomer, the quantiﬁcation of enantiomeric composition, and/or the determination of absolute conﬁguration. – The usual convention16 is followed whereby Dd values are expressed as the chemical shift of the (S)-MTPA derivative minus the (R)-MTPA derivative when using SR for the H nucleus concerned. For other CDAs such as MPA the CDA MTPA, i.e. DdH RS values are expressed; in this way, the signs of the Dd values for the and AMA, DdH one substrate tend to be the same irrespective of the CDA in use. For comparison of the chemical shift difference of geminal protons within the one molecule, no convention is yet in place and the Dd values are expressed as proR minus proS, i.e. DdH(RS) for the H nuclei concerned. oughly reviewed.16–18 The underlying principle is that nuclei (typ- ically, but not exclusively, 1H) on the same ligand extending from the stereogenic center will all exhibit the same net relative shield- ing/deshielding effect arising from the CDA, that is, the chemical shift in one derivatized substrate with the CDA minus the chemical shift of the substrate derivatized with the other enantiomer of the CDA (expressed as, e.g., DdðSRÞ –). The Dds in the other ligand should then be of opposite sign and these signs can then be related to which hemisphere the ligand extends, based upon the acknowledged16,19 preferred conformers of the CDA group in use, thereby yielding the conﬁguration of the substrate. Additionally for primary alcohols, the pattern of the chemical shift difference for the geminal protons of the hydroxyl carbon, proR minus proS, with one CDA versus the other CDA enantiomer (DdH(RS),91) has also been utilized16 for the determination of the absolute conﬁguration (e.g., in one case DdH(RS) is large, in the other case, DdH(RS) is small). This approach for assign- ing the absolute conﬁguration has also been applied to diols with a primary alcohol.20,21

It should be noted that the use of MTPA for the absolute conﬁg- uration determination has been deemed somewhat problematic,22 and even unreliable.16,19,23 This can be immediately evident from the occurrence of anomalous results, for example, Dds of the same sign for nuclei on different ligands or of opposite sign for nuclei on the same ligand, but even the seemingly consistent results have also been shown to be erroneous.16 Furthermore, it remains open to interpretation as to what magnitude is sufﬁcient for Dd to be considered reliable. Herein the question with regards to the abso- lute conﬁgurations of the dioxane rings in alnumycins A2 2 and A3 3 was addressed by both a conventional empirical approach and a simpliﬁed analysis of through-space NMR shieldings (TSNMRS) evaluation applied ﬁrst to the known conﬁguration8 of alnumycin A1 1 to substantiate the methodology. 2. Results and discussion 2.1. Relative conﬁguration and conformational analysis Although the chromatographic separation of alnumycins A1–3 1–3 into their six constituent stereoisomers proved challenging, 1, 2, and 3 were all obtained separately as C-1 inverse-epimeric pairs. The present identiﬁcation and past assignments of the in- verse-epimeric pair 1 were straightforward based on the 1H NMR spectroscopic data due to the chair conformation adopted by the dioxane ring. This was not the case for 2 and 3 and their structural analysis with respect to the dioxane ring was compounded by the fact that for each stereoisomer, the observed spectra were the aver- aged spectra of interconverting skew conformers (vide infra). The presence of two stereoisomers, in addition to the higher order of the spectra and signal overlap, greatly complicated the analysis of the 1H NMR spectra acquired in CDCl3.

The relative conﬁguration (10RS,40SR,50SR) of the dioxane ring for alnumycin A2 2 was realized by the NOE contacts gH10,H40 and gH10,H50 (Fig. 2). However, the observation of gH10 ,H40 requires that either an 10 S50 conformer and/or an 10 S30 conformer must be adopted by the structure. Furthermore, since an NOE between H-10 and one of the H-30 pair was also observed, the implication is for a dynamic equilib- rium that involves at least two skew conformers, for example, 10 S50 and 10 S30 , to account for the NOE contacts gH10,H30 and gH10,H50 [and separately arising from the 10 S50 and 10 S30 conformers, respectively]. Similar NOEs were observed for alnumycin A3 3 except for gH10,H50; therefore the conﬁguration must be different at C-50 in 3 relative to 2 (and furthermore, only at C-50) and thus is assigned as a relative dioxane ring conﬁguration of (10RS,40SR,50RS). In order to substanti- ate these conformational assertions, preliminary exploratory molec- ular modeling of 2a and 3a using density functional theory (DFT) Figure 2. was conducted and yielded several structures each for 2a and 3a with three and two low-energy ring conformations (Table 1) identi- ﬁed for 2a (10 S30 ; 20 S70 , and 10 S50 skew conformers) and 3a (70 S20 and 10 S30 skew conformers), respectively. Unfortunately, variable-tem- perature 1H NMR measurements at 500 MHz (down to (cid:2)55 (cid:3)C in CDCl3 and then repeated again in CD3OD down to (cid:2)95 (cid:3)C) failed to yield decoalescence of the 1H signals for either 2 or 3, although this is not surprising given the adopted skew conformations. Thus, the adopted conformations and dynamic interconversion complicated the 1H NMR spectroscopic analysis, they actually facilitated the con- ﬁgurations of 2 and 3 by the observation of pertinent NOEs. In order to reafﬁrm the NOE results obtained in CDCl3, 1H NMR spectra and 1D NOESY experiments of 2 and 3 were also acquired in C6D6 to alleviate some of the signal overlap. Fully consistent results to those obtained in CDCl3 were subsequently obtained (results not shown). The (1R)-conﬁguration has previously been established12 in both alnumycin A1 (1) and its biosynthetic precursor prealnumy- cin 4 by unequivocal matching of their quantum-chemically pre- dicted ECD spectra to the experimental spectra. This is because the C-1 conﬁguration uniquely determines the chiral skew of the plane encompassing the chromophore.12 The experi- mental ECD spectra (Fig. 3) of alnumycins A2 2 and A3 3 clearly indicated that they have the same C-1 conﬁguration as 1 and 4, that is, (1R), and furthermore they must therefore be C-1 inverse epimers given the intensity of the ECD spectra by comparison to 1 and 4 and the foregoing conclusion from the NMR spectra that they must be either epimers or inverse epimers.

For the chirooptical aspects, it is important that the change in conﬁguration does not interfere with the subunit to any signiﬁcant degree, for example, by causing a change in conformation thereby changing the chirooptical properties of the subunit, otherwise there may not be constructive/destructive interference between the compounds and its epimer/inverse epimer. For ECD measure- ments in the alnumycins, this is not a concern since the dioxo side- chain does not inﬂuence the electronic bands in any way, based on the observation and quantum-chemical calculations and, further- more, the sidechain does not effect the chromophore conformation since it is so distant from C-1. In order to independently conﬁrm the C-1 conﬁguration, and thus subsequently validate the presence of inverse epimers as well as to evaluate the holemicity of the C-1 stereogenic center, in alnumycins A1–3 1–3, analysis using the CDA MTPACl13,14 was conducted. Indeed, it was of particular interest to ascertain if the epimer/inverse epimer conundrum could readily be resolved by the use of a CDA. Additionally, the determination of the absolute conﬁgurations of the dioxane rings in 2 and 3 was also attempted by ﬁrst evaluating the results of 1 for which the absolute conﬁgu- rations have been assigned8 and then parlay the results towards the absolute conﬁguration determinations for 2 and 3 using 1 as a validation standard. Two approaches were considered, ﬁrst by conventional empirical analysis using the results of 1 in compari- son to 2 and 3; and then by evaluation of a simpliﬁed TSNMRS methodology, again using the results of 1 as the basis for substan- tiating the conclusions. 2.3.1. The C-1 conﬁguration and inverse-epimeric relationships in alnumycins A1–3 1–3

First, (R)-prealnumycin 4 was separately derivatized with both enantiomers of MTPACl and examined by 1H NMR. An impressive 0.454 ppm chemical shift difference between the corresponding (cid:3) was observed for the two derivatives with H- H-1 protons DdSR H1 1 in the R-MTPA derivative being more shielded. Moreover, the majority of the DdSR H1 value seems to arise from additional shielding in the R-MTPA derivative since relative to the H-1 in 4, the H-1 in the (R)-MTPA derivative is shielded by ca. 0.38 ppm. Since the magnetic anisotropy of the newly introduced phenyl group is con- sidered to be the only effective source of additional shielding in these derivatives, it was therefore considered judicious to only compare conformations where the phenyl group is beneath and proximal to H-1 with its ring plane facing upward to H-1 to effect signiﬁcant shielding. If the phenyl group is displaced relative to H- 1, or the plane of the phenyl group orientated away from H-1, any T. Oja et al. / Tetrahedron: Asymmetry 23 (2012) 670–682 shielding experienced by H-1 would likely be inconsequential. The construction and geometry optimization of pertinent conforma- tions for each derivative of 4 (Fig. 4), and assuming a (1R)-conﬁg- uration for 4, revealed that the H-1 in the (R)-MTPA derivative should in fact experience sizeable TSNMRS arising from the phenyl group magnetic anisotropy, whereas the H-1 in the (S)-MTPA derivative should only experience marginal shielding due to their relative dispositions to their respective phenyl groups by subse- quent shielding calculations using a GIAO methodology. For these two conformations, the calculated DdSR H1 was 1.26 ppm, that is, H- 1 in the (R)-MTPA derivative is more shielded, thus implying that these are the decisive conformations.

Thus, it can be concluded that the C-1 conﬁguration in naturally occurring prealnumycin 4 is (R) by CDA analysis and that this is in agreement with the determination by ECD.12 It should be noted that the enantiopurity was found, within the limits of detection, to be effectively 100% (i.e., the sample was holemic). This result also implies that each of the alnumycins A1–3 1–3 should consist of C-1 inverse-epimeric pairs rather than C-1 epimeric pairs since 1–3 have been shown to be biosynthetically derived from 4.11,24 In contrast to typical applications of Mosher’s method, or CDAs in general, for the determination of the absolute conﬁguration,16–18 where the OH or NH group is directly linked to the stereogenic center (a-chiral systems) or at most only two bonds distant (b-chi- ral systems); in this system the stereogenic center is three bonds distant from the site of attachment of the MTPA. Nevertheless, in successful analysis demonstrates the efﬁcacy, which may be attrib- uted to the rigid nature of the isochromanequinone framework.

Next, the tris-(R)-MTPA derivatives of alnumycins A1–3 1–3 were prepared from (S)-MTPACl and examined by 1H NMR. The chemical shifts of the H-1 protons (dH1s) in tris-(R)-MTPA-deriva- tized 1a and 1b readily identiﬁed the two isomers as having an (R)-conﬁguration for C-1 based on the foregoing results of (R)-pre- alnumycin 4. This alone indicates that the stereochemical relation- ship between 1a and 1b is inverse epimeric since the dioxane rings in 1a and 1b must have the same internal relative conﬁguration based on NMR analysis,8,12 that is, they must have opposite abso- lute conﬁgurations to each other in order to render a disparity be- tween the two compounds.12 Similarly, the enantiopurity of the C- 1 stereogenic center in 1a and 1b was found, within the limits of detection, to be effectively 100%. Most notably however, the dH1 shifts for alnumycins A1a 1a and A1b 1b were not particularly differentiated from each other and the chemical shift difference for H-1 of 1a minus H-1 of 1b (cid:4) for the tris-R-MTPA derivatives DdabðRÞ was only |0.004| ppm, which is even less than for underivatized 1 for which Ddab H1 was (cid:2)0.014 ppm. The unequivocal suggestion of these results is that the C-1 stereogenic center in 1a and 1b must be the same while the C-10, C-40, and C-50 stereogenic centers must be of opposite conﬁgurations in the two isomers, that is, the two compounds 1a and 1b constitute a pair of inverse epimers. Alnumycins A2 2 and A3 3 provided similar re- sults (see Tables 3 and 4, and Experimental Section 4.8), thus pro- viding a clear indication for the efﬁcacy of using a CDA for differentiation between a case of a pair of epimers or a pair of in- verse epimers when the pertinent site (C-1 in this instance) is suf- ﬁciently far apart from the other stereogenic centers, that is, there should only be a section-limited response (i.e. independency of the subunits containing the stereogenic centers) for the applied tech- nique, a requirement expressed previously.12 Furthermore, the analysis culminating in the conclusion of inverse epimers over epi- mers would remain valid even if direct analysis of the C-1 conﬁg- uration (i.e., by MTPA derivatization of the hydroxyl at C-10) was not possible. 2.3.2. Absolute conﬁguration of the dioxane ring in alnumycins A1–3 1–3 Although a sizeable and expanding collection of systems has been studied16–18 (e.g., a-chiral secondary alcohols, b-chiral pri- mary alcohols, and polyols such as a,a-chiral 1,2-, 1,3-, and 1,4- prim/sec,sec-diols20,21,25,26) in terms of the application of CDAs for absolute conﬁguration determination, systems akin to the dioxane ring of the alnumycins A1–3 1–3 have not previously been exam- ined, viz. b-chiral primary, a-chiral secondary 1,3-diols. The quintessential basis for the determination of the absolute conﬁguration using a CDA is the assessment of the preferred confor- mations adopted by the derivatives. Since it is the conformational preferences which underlie the models and their application, any alteration of the preference, and even the possibility of differential conformer preference be- tween the diastereomers must be considered,26 which undermines the premise altogether. Thus, the selected probes should only have a limited extent in their effect and ideally there are no accompany- ing effects such as conformational changes. Since it is desirable that no perturbation of the chiral section occurs, chirooptical methods are obviously preferred over derivatization. Otherwise only singular effects should be engaged, for example, monoderiv- atization, and while inducing a chiral environment, do not effect a concurrent conformational change. Thus ECD was found to work successfully for the C-1 conﬁguration and while MTPA derivatiza- tion worked successfully for alnumycin A1 1, it was not successful for alnumycins A2 2 and A3 3. In principle, the CDA problem can be addressed by an ab initio approach involving comprehensive molecular modeling incorporating a full conformational search and analysis concomitant with energy evaluation followed by cal- culation of the chemical shifts spanning the conformational do- main and appropriately weighted according to their Boltzmann distribution.28–31 Needless to say, this can be both challenging and prohibitive with regards to demanding a substantial invest- ment in effort given the ﬂexibility and size of the MTPA group in addition to the molecule itself. Moreover, reliable results are only likely to be forthcoming via exhaustive high-level calculations. 2.4. Stereochemical aspects

Although alnumycins A1 1 and A3 3 each constitute a pair of C-1 inverse epimers, 1 and 3 are related in the sense that for one of the A1 pair, its C-10 epimer is one of the A3 pair (e.g., 1a and 3b) and similarly for the other A1 isomer and the other A3 isomer (Fig. 5). This is signiﬁcant because the C-10 stereogenic center is potentially labile under appropriate conditions resulting in epi- merization and 1a and 3b can thus potentially interconvert. Fur- thermore, transacetalization may also occur giving rise to inversion of conﬁguration at both C-40 and C-50, since the C4 unit spanning C30–C60 can be reversed such that C-30 and C-60 are inter- changed, and thus concomitantly, also C-40 and C-50. Such a trans- formation would result in the interconversion of 1a and 3a for example. Thus any of the four stereoisomers 1a, 1b, 3a, and 3b could potentially yield any of the other three in this set by fairly innocuous processes. Indeed, it was proven by feeding experi- ments24 of [5(cid:4)13 C:C-1–5]-labeled ribose in a culture broth of C-4' epimer of 1α; C-5' epimer of 3α (R) (R) (S) (S) C-4' epimer of 1β; C-5' epimer of 3β Streptomyces sp. CM020 that the ﬁve carbon atoms of the dioxane ring all originated from ribose. Moreover, the postulated inter- change of C-30 and C-60 was conﬁrmed by the feeding24 of [1(cid:4)13C: C-5]-labeled ribose wherein one stereoisomer of 1, the C-60 carbon showed a greater enhancement while in the other stereoisomer, it was the C-30 carbon that showed greater enhancement, thereby alluding to the proposed reversal of the C4 unit.

On the other hand, alnumycin A2 2 can only be converted into either alnumycin A1 1, for example, 2a to 1a, or A3 3, for example 2b to 3b, by a process inverting the conﬁguration of either C-40 or C-50 independently, that is, without concomitant inversion of the other. Thus, the occurrence of 2 is much more difﬁcult to explain biosynthetically, but could occur by enzymatic-catalyzed keto-enol isomerization steps, or by oxidation–reduction processes, and which may of course also apply to the alnumycin A1 1 and A3 3 pairs. It should be noted that the C-10 epimers of 2, representing a fourth pair of diastereomers of alnumycin A, were not identiﬁed in the biological extracts. However, despite the fact that they were not observed, it could be anticipated that the (1R,10R,40R,50R)- and (1R,10S,40S,50S)-stereoisomers could occur naturally based on the likely interchange between 1 and 3 which can also apply to 2. Whether thermodynamic and/or kinetic restraints prevail in limit- ing the amount of this unseen pair of stereoisomers remains an open question. Nevertheless, it can be anticipated that the stereo- chemical elucidation of these natural products may provide an insight into the role of the proteins involved in the biosynthesis of 1–3 and the precise mechanistic pathway of their formation,24 an approach that may well be potentially broadly applicable.

As a ﬁnal consideration, it is worth contemplating why the ear- lier accounts6,7 reported only the presence of one stereoisomer of alnumycin A, this may have been due to the different Streptomyces strains utilized or the different growing conditions yielding greater stereospeciﬁcity. It is also possible that during previous isolation work, an unintended fractionation of alnumycin A occurred during chromatography and thus the presence of other products was inad- vertently overlooked. Since alnumycin A1 1 elutes ﬁrst under the normal phase conditions, this was the compound isolated and re- ported on.6–8 The presence of a pair of stereoisomers for 1 may have also eluded6,7 detection since the degree of signal disparity varied greatly with the prevailing sample conditions under which they were examined§; in this particular examination the spectra for 1a and 1b were very similar. Incidentally, the diastereomeric pre- dominance, 1a:1b, observed here was reversed in comparison to Tatsuta,8 although variation in the 1a:1b ratio was evident from sample to sample. A slight perturbation from chromatography was evident to account for this, in addition to any variation arising from bacterial strain production. In general, in order to ascertain the absolute conﬁguration by CDA analysis, there either needs to be in place a proven and consis- tent precedent resulting from a comprehensive examination of compounds of known absolute conﬁguration with similar struc- tural elements as in the present system to validate that the appli- cation works at an empirical level, or a thorough and rigorous modeling study needs to be undertaken. The problem herein is that unprecedented structures are involved: b-chiral primary, a-chiral secondary 1,3 diols with the b-chiral stereogenic center located within a ring. Furthermore, the conformational mobility of the dioxane ring and the steric interaction between the MTPA groups in the derivatized alnumycins A2 2 and A3 3 compromised the chances of a successful analysis using the CDA MTPACl, either via empirical comparisons to alnumycin A1 1 or by a simpliﬁed com- putational TSNMRS methodology. Molecular modeling: geometry optimization, vibrational analysis, thermochemistry, TSNMRS, and NMR chemical shift calculations

The DFT quantum chemical calculations were performed using Gaussian0940 (version A.01) and analyzed using GUIs GaussView (versions 3.07 and 5.0.8) and GaussSum41 (version 2.2). Structures were ﬁrst geometry-optimized using the M06-2X hybrid meta density functional42,43 with the 6-31G(d) basis set followed by vibrational analysis and thermochemistry calculations at the same level of theory conducted to conﬁrm that the optimized structures were true minima on the potential energy surface by not providing imaginary frequencies and to obtain the thermodynamic contribu- tions at 298.15 K and 1 atm wherein frequencies were left un- scaled. Two procedural protocols were utilized for the optimization/thermodynamics. Protocol A [(R)-prealnumycin 4 and alnumycin A1 1] consisted of optimization in tandem with vibrational analysis and thermochemistry calculations and invok- ing the keyword freq = noraman for the latter call; protocol B [alnumycins A2a 2a and A3a 3a] consisted of initial optimization followed by re-optimization in tandem with vibrational analysis and thermochemistry calculations and invoking for this second step the keywords opt = tight and int = ultraﬁne for the former call and freq = noraman for the latter call. Protocol B was useful for eliminating cases of imaginary frequencies and obtaining more accurate values for DG(cid:3). Absolute chemical shieldings were calcu- lated using the GIAO method44 at the M06-2X/cc-pVTZ level of the- ory. All calculations were performed in the gas phase.

For (R)-prealnumycin 4, two stable conformers have previ- ously12 been found, one with an axially orientated n-propyl group and the other with it equatorially orientated, from free-hand for- mulated starting structures.
